\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.50}{\ignorespaces Performance comparison of the E2E autoencoder against the modular relay-based approaches. The E2E system does not achieve lower BER than the two-hop DF relay.}}{108}{figure.caption.139}%
\setforeignlanguage {english}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.51}{\ignorespaces Unknown-ISI two-hop relay BER vs.\ SNR (S1: unknown ISI $\to $ AWGN). AF/DF plateau at a non-monotonic floor around 0.18--0.23; the MLP relay breaks away toward the noise floor at high SNR. Companion scenarios (S2: ISI $\to $ Rayleigh, S3: nonlinear-bias $\to $ AWGN, S4: Rayleigh-to-Rayleigh control) are provided alongside this figure in the accompanying results directory.}}{116}{figure.caption.140}%
\setforeignlanguage {english}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.52}{\ignorespaces Viterbi MLSE with genie vs.\ pilot-estimated channel taps, unknown ISI $\to $ AWGN. The 200-symbol (0.2\% overhead) pilot estimate tracks the genie curve closely at every SNR. A companion Rayleigh-hop2 scenario is provided alongside this figure.}}{117}{figure.caption.141}%
\setforeignlanguage {english}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.53}{\ignorespaces Memoryless unknown-phase channel (F1, DBPSK): DF and MLP track each other closely at every SNR (maximum gap 0.0075 across the sweep), consistent with the expectation that classical detection is not disadvantaged when the unknown channel parameter has no memory. Companion unknown-gain (F2) and per-branch-asymmetry (F3) figures are provided alongside this one.}}{118}{figure.caption.142}%
\setforeignlanguage {english}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.54}{\ignorespaces Composite channel cascade (ISI $\times $ PA nonlinearity $\times $ unknown phase). AF/DF-diff plateau near 0.25; Viterbi-diff is ahead of both MLP sizes in the 8--12\,dB transition region, while all three converge by 20\,dB. The 169- and 1153-parameter MLPs perform near-identically, indicating that additional capacity does not help once the task saturates.}}{119}{figure.caption.143}%
\setforeignlanguage {english}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.55}{\ignorespaces Blind regime, random ISI per trial, no pilots. CMA-blind and MLP-169 converge to near-identical BER by 20\,dB (0.0024 vs.\ 0.0024). Viterbi-blind's decision-directed channel bootstrap is visibly less stable than the other two: its 95\% confidence interval at 10\,dB is roughly 9$\times $ wider than the MLP's (\(\pm 0.088\) vs.\ \(\pm 0.010\)), reflecting occasional bootstrap-estimate failures on individual trials rather than a difference in mean performance.}}{120}{figure.caption.144}%
\setforeignlanguage {english}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.56}{\ignorespaces (a) Viterbi payload BER vs.\ pilot count at 10\,dB: performance is flat and below the zero-pilot MLP/CMA references down to 10 pilots, then collapses sharply at 5 pilots (0.119) -- consistent with an identifiability floor when too few pilot symbols remain to resolve the channel's degrees of freedom. (b) Block-length sweep with a fixed 10-pilot preamble: pilot overhead falls from 25\% (L=40) to 1\% (L=1000) as block length grows, while the MLP relay carries zero pilot overhead throughout.}}{121}{figure.caption.145}%
\setforeignlanguage {english}
\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {A.57}{\ignorespaces (a) Per-symbol flop count: Viterbi MLSE grows as $M^L$ while the MLP relay is constant in both $M$ and $L$; at the smallest configuration (BPSK, $L=3$) Viterbi is in fact cheaper per-flop (64 vs.\ 330) -- the MLP's advantage is in scaling, not in absolute cost at the smallest setting. (b) Measured wall-clock inference time (\texttt {relaynet}'s own Viterbi and MLP implementations, BPSK, $L=3$): the MLP is 30.8$\times $--85.1$\times $ faster across signal lengths 1{,}000--50{,}000 symbols, reflecting a vectorized batched matrix multiply versus an inherently sequential per-symbol trellis scan; this ratio is specific to this numpy/Python implementation, not a universal hardware-independent claim.}}{122}{figure.caption.146}%
